<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Friday evening news posts from Alan</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=326970" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/044816.html">At least say SOMETHING about Faydedar</a></B><P>

VI, we have REPEATEDLY told you there is a problem on some servers with this epic mob needed to complete druid epic quest. With nearly every cleric or rogue over 50 wielding their epics, why do you absolutly REFUSE to even look at this issue? <P>

<B>Well, we did some tests.<P>

We found a server where we know he popped last night. We compared the data from that server to one that people are claiming that he does not pop. The data matches.<P>

We're pretty sure that he is popping as planned.<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/045210.html">Ragefire poofs again</a></B><P>

On Wednesday night on Innoruuk, after a month of organizing repeated ad-hoc Naggy raids, living through Sol B zone repops, and getting bum-rushed by all the other Ragefire-capable guilds on the server, my guild finally managed to get Ragefire to ourselves. We owned him. Unfortunately, about 1/3 of our people went LD during the fight, and an LD level 60 Ranger landed the killing blow. So Ragefire poofed.<P>

<B>It sure seems odd that this is only happening to Ragefire... I have no idea why. I'll pass this on to the team.<P>

Alan</B><P>

<B>Ok, this whole thing was Alan getting confused.<P>

There was special code put in several months ago that prevented nearly any possibility of a corpse poofing if the NPC is over 54th level. I was right there.<P>

But recently, a few weeks ago, we added some code to deal with a unique NPC situation (that I'm not going to go into…) that might have been causing corpses to poof is the kill was assigned to a Link Dead PC over 54th level. This will be changed with the next patch.<P>

I was confused and thought that this change was already in.<P>

I'm sorry about the confusion.<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/045219.html">NOW,AFTER NERFING SCREAMING TERROR....</a></B><P>

You can come out and show us your real face absor, that you and VI generaly HATE necros and want to remove them from the game by making em useless at the high level. ST was one of the reasons, why we were invited in groups. Now we have to wait with a 5 men party at the entrance of sebilis, because we cant get a chanter. HOW BALLANCED.<P>

<B>I said what?<P>

I don't remember saying anything at all about any changes to Screaming Terror. If I did, please post it here and I'll explain it (right now I'm not on my machine and don't have access to my files...).<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/045291.html">New Nercomancers on Raids Thread</a></B><P>

<I>The old threads were getting a bit nasty and were wandering. Let's not have that happen here.
Let me sum up my thoughts on this whole thing.<P>

Necromancers are just fine, in all aspects of the game, with one possible exception.<P>

On raids they can find a lot to do up to and after the encounter with the boss mob. But in that encounter some necromancers don't feel that they have enough to do, or feel that what they can do isn't what they want to be doing.<P>

In this thread I would like to keep to one narrow focus. What things could be done to give necromancers more to do in that one encounter, without improving their power in other situations?<P>

It's a very narrow question, and a very hard one to answer. Here are the ideas that I've seen that won't work, or won't happen:<P>

DoT stacking: We're probably not going to allow more DoTs to stack than already do. And this would have an impact far beyond the scope here, it would increase the power of necromancers across the board.<P>

Unresistable Lifetap: Probably never going to happen. I understand the whole concept of Lifetap to power mana transfer. I'm just telling you with a pretty firm tone, that it's really not likely to happen.<P>

Mana Transfer: The rate will probably not be improved. As I've said before, currently necromancers can convert 1 hit point into 1 mana. Right now they can give that 1 mana to a cleric (as an example) for the cost of about 2.5 mana. The cleric can convert that mana into about 2 hit points. That's the right ratio, really. There shouldn't be a time when the amount that can be returned is higher than the amount that is given out.<P>

Poofing: with the next patch, this should be pretty much fixed… let me copy one of my other posts:</I><P>

"Ok, this whole thing was Alan getting confused.<P>

There was special code put in several months ago that prevented nearly any possibility of a corpse poofing if the NPC is over 54th level. I was right there.<P>

But recently, a few weeks ago, we added some code to deal with a unique NPC situation (that I'm not going to go into…) that might have been causing corpses to poof is the kill was assigned to a Link Dead PC over 54th level. This will be changed with the next patch.<P>

I was confused and thought that this change was already in.<P>

I'm sorry about the confusion.<P>

Alan"<P>

<I>In any case, let's leave this one off the list until we see how things go post-patch. I have noticed, though, that the only complaint I've seen was about Ragefire… I wouldn't be worried about poofing due to DoTs anymore. At least try it out.<P>

Issues that we can discuss:<P>

Ignite Bones: I'm willing to suggest some change to remove the skeleton. I think to do that we need to have something that does the same sort of thing, but I don't know what that is. This spell will probably never be changed into a standard direct damage spell. I like some of the ideas (like changing the tinting on the target), but unfortunately most of them don't seem possible technically. I'll keep thinking up ideas. Post any you have here.<P>

Group Feign Death: I haven't mentioned this idea to the team yet. I suppose that there might be a lot of reasons not to implement this idea…<P>

Making pets immune to fear: This probably won't happen. Then we'd have to do the same for magicians (not an inherently bad thing, but it has broad repercussions), and there's PvP to consider. But I think I have some interesting ideas along these lines that might work out. I want to here other ideas along these lines.<P>

Possessing the pet: that's a cute as heck idea (maybe 'cute' is the wrong word…). Another one that I'll mention to the team. But keep in mind that I'm not really looking for totally new stuff. I'm not advocating that we start making up new spells and whole new concepts. It would be hard to justify spending a ton of time making new concepts at this point. But it's certainly interesting…<P>

Essence Emerald: I'm kind of in favor of using this device as a way of changing things. It's a very expensive casting cost… For example I kind of liked the idea of allowing the mana transfer spell to be usable on others, considering the cost.<P>

Unrelated Issues (meaning that I'm mentioning them here so that you don't have to bring them up…) :<P>

I'm aware that Track Corpse doesn't work. I'm going to ask about that.<P>

The epic weapon. It's not really related to this anyhow, and I am already very aware how you all feel about it.<P>

Defoliate: If someone wants to start a new thread about which things they think should be affected by this spell, go for it. But it's not part of the focus of this thread.<P>

I may have missed some…<P>

Keep in mind that I understand that many of you are not happy with a support role on raids. I'm fairly convinced that it is perfectly fine for a necromancer to act in that role during the final battle of the raid. But I'm open to ideas (barring the ones that I've already vetoed) that would make them more aggressive at that one final battle.<P>

Alan</I><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/042756-5.html">Inspect Option</a></B><P>

"1 - Toggle for turning off your own ability to inspect someone else - this is hands down a good idea, as it causes a bit of lag on your end as thier equipment pops up on your screen, and with the mouselook the way it is, inspections can be quite inadvertant."<P>

<B>Sorry, didn't read the whole thread. My new computer is a bit messed up, so I'm using someone else's to try to catch up.<P>

This is an interesting idea. I agree that something should probably be done to make it so that mouselook doesn't inspect. This would do it (though there might be a better way).<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/045276.html">The death of Necros (Part Three) by Pretorian-your-god</a></B><P>

sinseraph wrote: "here's the numbers behind this situation you described Absor: 
L49 Lich takes 32 hp and gives you 20 mana every tick, which is 6 seconds. 
L44 Covetous Subversion takes 300 mana and gives 100 to the target player."<P>

<B>You must have missed my previous post.<P>

Lich takes 20 or 21 hit points and gives you 20 mana every tick… Lich is being treated as a PvP spell and is doing 33% less damage to you.<P>

As for Covetous Subversion, the point of my number comparison was in response to those that want a 1:1 mana gift spell, and why it probably won't happen. Even at 2:1 it would be too much (plug it into my calculation).</B><P>

Xdammedx wrote: "As for the lich thing, it totally sucks that the rest of us have to suffer because of a BUG on 3 total servers out of over 30."<P>

<B>Actually, you're not 'suffering' from this bug. You're gaining from it. It reduces the damage that the spell does to the caster. You're getting a 1:1 ratio of hit points for mana, instead of a 3:2 ratio as was intended.</B><P>

Scriabin said: "Frankly, "interesting" is about the last thing from our uber, Vox-soloing minds. We just want it to not be banned from use! Removing the skel effect would accomplish this nicely."<P>

<B>Ok, I'll admit to being a bit baffled by this who banned from using the spell thing.<P>

Can't a smart group prepare for this effect and act accordingly? I'd be a bit surprised if you told me no…</B><P>

Velespio wrote: "Lich does not take 32 hp, it takes 26 hp. You claimed we get a hp to mana ratio of 1 : 1. Were you mistaken on this or are you sure? Demi lich is 48 hp for 30 mana supposedly, 48 hp for 48 mana seems like a lot. Or were you referring to 48 hp * 33% = 16 48 hp - 16 hp (for pvp coding) = 32 hp. According to this demi lich gives 32 mana for 32 hp and lich gives 26 mana for 26 hp /shrug just food for thought."<P>

<B>Yup, I'm sure. The damage taken by the player is reduced in code by 33% because the code sees it as a player damaging a player. So your last line seems right, 32 for 32…<P>

I'm going to open a new thread on this, to consolidate my thoughts.<P>

Alan</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
